ou4GRQjOh-PX_oD_zGI-6]. Based on his assumptions, he found that Pipe was th=
e cheapest cost of capital for a fast-growing, subscription-based business.=20
Again, the full post is worth a read if you=E2=80=99re choosing among the d=
ifferent financing methods. The takeaway is that Pipe costs less than ventu=
re debt or RBF in terms of rate, and much less than both venture capital an=
d venture debt (when warrants are included) in terms of value given to inve=
stors, assuming that the business is growing and trades at market multiples=
=2E One commenter pointed out that with=20=
interest rates where they are, ventur=
e debt is going for 5% in some cases, but even at 5%, when warrants and lie=
ns on the business are considered, Pipe is much cheaper.=20
The comparison doesn=E2=80=99t even take into account the fact that fundrai=
sing, whether venture capital or venture debt, is a time-consuming, defocus=
ing process. When a company is in fundraising mode, it often requires the f=
ull focus of the senior leadership team, pulling them away from activities =
that would help grow the business. And the legal fees can be killer!=20
What about just discounting to get customers to pay annually instead of mon=
thly? Pipe wins here, too.=20
I did an informal survey of some subscription businesses that came to mind.=20
Even at $0.85 cents on the dollar, which is a much lower bid than most of P=
ipe=E2=80=99s customers trade at, Pipe would still be a cheaper financing m=
ethod than the discounts that leading subscription businesses offer their c=
ustomers to pay the full annual amount upfront. At 16.67 - 30.95%, those di=
scounts are effectively incredibly expensive loans!=20
Plus, according to a Pipe customer survey, annual discounts only entice ~7%=
 of customers to pay upfront instead of monthly. Just like the subscription=
 businesses want the money upfront, their customers want to keep their mone=
y as long as possible, and so the annual discount trade rarely clears. If a=
 subscription customer is a SaaS company and wanted to be really smart, I s=
uppose they could trade their own subscriptions on Pipe for a 5-10% discoun=
t to annualized cash flow and then use that cash to pay for the other subsc=
ription upfront saving 20-30% =F0=9F=A4=AF
There=E2=80=99s one more important thing to note on annual discounts versus=
 Pipe. Subscription businesses are valued on a multiple of top line revenue=
=2E Because of the way accounting works,=
 when a business offers an annual dis=
count, they are giving away top line revenue, but when they sell monthly su=
bscriptions at full price and sell their recurring revenue on Pipe, they ge=
t to keep the full amount in the top line, supercharging their valuation.=20
Let=E2=80=99s take Slack, the company that I love so much despite the fact =
that its performance is dragging my entire portfolio down. If 7% of its cus=
tomers choose to pay annually with a 16.67% discount, and it trades at a 19=
=2E9x EV/LTM Revenue multiple, it=E2=80=99=
s giving up $200 million in enterpr=
ise value by discounting instead of using Pipe!=20
That=E2=80=99s enterprise value that I, as a beleaguered shareholder, would=
 love to have in my pocket.
Why Now: Pipe=E2=80=99s Flywheel=20
By now, we=E2=80=99ve established that Pipe should exist. It=E2=80=99s a br=
illiant idea that helps businesses fund themselves more efficiently and giv=
es investors access to a new asset class that strips out all of the noise a=
nd directs those sweet, sweet recurring revenue cash flows right into their=
 veins.=20
But it=E2=80=99s fucking hard to start a new asset class on a new exchange.=
 It=E2=80=99s a two-sided marketplace problem: you need to both convince co=
mpanies to sell their revenues and investors to buy them. That=E2=80=99s pa=
rt of the reason that Pipe has raised so much money for a company its size.=
 When Pipe announced its seed extension, Hurst highlighted this challenge:=20
We are connecting SaaS companies with investors, and in order to do that, l=
iquidity needs to be in the marketplace. Only a small portion of the new fi=
nancing will go to core operations=E2=80=94we run lean and mean=E2=80=94and=
 a vast majority of the money will go into the marketplace, so as more SaaS=
 companies sign up, there will be liquidity.
This is what the challenge looks like in practice:=20
Pipe needs to simultaneously attract companies willing to sell their recurr=
ing revenue and investors willing to buy it.
If it attracts a lot of companies and few investors, there will be more sup=
ply than demand and investors=E2=80=99 bids will be low - maybe they would =
pay $0.70 for $1 worth of revenue.=20
If bids are low, companies will leave and find better ways to fund the busi=
ness, including offering bigger discounts to entice customers to pay upfron=
t.=20
If Pipe attracts a lot of investors but few companies, there won=E2=80=99t =
be enough recurring revenue streams for investors to buy, and it will remai=
n small.=20
One way to solve that in the early days is by buying liquidity - supporting=
 the market by either buying recurring revenue streams itself or by paying =
more to bring companies onto the platform. Pipe is good enough at what it d=
oes, and well-financed enough, that it would have solved the chicken-and-eg=
g problem either way, it just would have cost a lot upfront.=20
The only thing better than being good, though, is being good and lucky. Alm=
ost all of the factors that I wrote about in Software is Eating the Markets=
 [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkMFuhSAQRb9GdhoEUVyw6Ka_YVBGpSr4YOx7=
_n15mrRpwoRkbmbO3DtohMmHU-0-IjkihM4aVdZMclG1xKjKlFJIYmM3BoBN21VhOIDsR7_aQaP=
17pqglAkyK1lKkLKpG0kbzkVdyZZS2o8tNwLMKMmb0-nDWHADKPiGcHoHZFUz4h4z_pGxz_Scx9=
4H66YiHn1EPSzF4Lck7KmiH_GpA-Q25pBOcFOOM-SbDgtgJFYxymhJWVsywXldlMVjei3TY399i=
ayi28T-bSVB_eKSvMx6g_USksku_dvhLJ4dON2vYG7_eCd22cFzB-XgGVdAhHA336EI3tRVw0ii=
GZ-yc3-gH0JuggI] are coming together to smash through Pipe=E2=80=99s liquid=
ity challenge. =20
SaaS and subscription businesses, from Zoom to Peloton to paid newsletters,=
 are growing incredibly fast during COVID, creating more supply of recurrin=
g revenue streams.=20
Interest rates are at all-time lows, and investors are looking for yield.
Investors are particularly interested in SaaS and subscription business com=
panies as evidenced by their equities=E2=80=99 outperformance in the market=
, and are more than happy to buy exposure to the cash flows directly withou=
t paying a huge multiple.
Pipe sits right in the middle of those two, providing an exchange on which =
companies can earn cash today and investors can buy the revenue streams the=
y want.=20
More liquidity means more transactions, which builds trust in the asset cla=
ss, and more bids competing for revenue streams means better bids, which at=
tracts more companies.
This is Pipe=E2=80=99s flywheel and network effect: more bids =E2=86=92 bet=
ter prices =E2=86=92 more companies =E2=86=92 more bids.
In many ways, Pipe=E2=80=99s flywheel is like Opendoor=E2=80=99s [https://e=
mail.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkNtuwyAMhp-m3DVKICcuuNjNXiMi4CYsCabgrM3bjzbSpkk=
-SP5l__JnNMGE8VABE7E9QRycVVXLe9HUkllV26pveubScIsAm3arorgDC_u4OqPJoX9vlCVv2K=
yktLqVemyN7LWsOyuF5CAt77iw7c2wl8-gd-vAG1DwDfFAD2xVM1FIF_Fx4Z85PNKI0fmpSPuYS=
JulMLhlIeRcPJrletbHjOlKM0S4YgBvESNzipe8rEouK94I0RZVcZ-ey3QPz6_mUpfbxP-dZVH9=
-mV5mfUG61vIXw65b7t3dAzg9biCPQHQiez9Dx0BlIdHWoEI4jl8UWlE19YdZ9nNYobn_4x-AOl=
Cg2k]. More transactions lead to better pricing which leads to more transac=
tions.=20
Pipe is the cheapest and most efficient capital for SaaS and subscription b=
usinesses today. The beauty of a marketplace or exchange, though, is that o=
nce you get it going, it just keeps getting better over time. As Pipe conti=
nues to turn the flywheel, it will become even more of a no-brainer tool in=
 the SaaS and subscription business financing toolkit. And it=E2=80=99s jus=
t getting started=E2=80=A6=20
Matching Financing to Businesses=20
Pipe is just getting started.=20
First, it focused just on SaaS businesses.=20
Then, it opened up to all subscription businesses.=20
Next, Pipe is developing a Recurring Revenue Offering that allows companies=
 to pre-sell future subscription revenue to raise even more money.=20
In the future, Pipe will provide a greater and greater number of financing =
alternatives custom built for tech businesses.=20
Pipe is in the business of creating Business-Funding Fit. Its skills -- pul=
ling in companies=E2=80=99 financial data via APIs, assigning ratings based=
 on that data, attracting investors, providing liquidity, and managing seam=
less ongoing financial transactions -- will be extensible to many more subs=
cription-based business models over time.=20
Think internet bills, cable bills, cell phone bills, membership fees, fitne=
ss app memberships, creator economy subscriptions=E2=80=A6 if it=E2=80=99s =
a digital subscription, Pipe should be able to turn MRR into ARR and provid=
e access to cheap, efficient capital. If I ever turn on paid subscriptions =
for Not Boring, Pipe is going to be my first call. =20
If you run a SaaS or digital subscription business, sign up for Pipe [https=
://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuwyAQ_BpztHg6-MChUpXfsLDZOjQ2EFja-O9L4kO=
llVa7o9nZmcUirDEfJsWCpBbIk3eGDVwLJUfijHRMK018mb4ywG79ZjBXIKnOm18s-hjeDEq5Ij=
cj5xEUsFk7J-Qw6mFkIAdOHdVCi3EhL53JVuchLGDgB_IRA5DN3BBT6cRHx6-tbEp98gn6Je5tL=
H4NNXXimuGrE58hYolzzD6sxBtOOWWUj4wrIYae9Y_1eV8f6fmtOkn3lfelzgXtcn9dI9k0-klu=
8P1md9jeQLM0tb7X4PGYINh5A3e6xTOf9_N4JDABfssGiJDP5SsCJS6DvHDS1FxsSYV_oT8bCns=
b] to keep more equity in your team=E2=80=99s pockets.
If you work for a SaaS or digital subscription business, tell your CEO and =
finance team to sign up for Pipe [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtu=
wyAQ_BpztHg6-MChUpXfsLDZOjQ2EFja-O9L4kOllVa7o9nZmcUirDEfJsWCpBbIk3eGDVwLJUf=
ijHRMK018mb4ywG79ZjBXIKnOm18s-hjeDEq5Ijcj5xEUsFk7J-Qw6mFkIAdOHdVCi3EhL53JVu=
