1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Again, the full=
 post is worth a read if you&#8217;re choosing among the different financin=
g methods. The takeaway is that Pipe costs less than venture debt or RBF in=
 terms of rate, and much less than both venture capital and venture debt (w=
hen warrants are included) in terms of value given to investors, assuming t=
hat the business is growing and trades at market multiples. One commenter p=
ointed out that with interest rates where they are, venture debt is going f=
or 5% in some cases, but even at 5%, when warrants and liens on the busines=
s are considered, Pipe is much cheaper. </p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The comparison doesn&#=
8217;t even take into account the fact that fundraising, whether venture ca=
pital or venture debt, is a time-consuming, defocusing process. When a comp=
any is in fundraising mode, it often requires the full focus of the senior =
leadership team, pulling them away from activities that would help grow the=
 business. And the legal fees can be killer! </p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">What about just d=
iscounting to get customers to pay annually instead of monthly? Pipe wins h=
